    10	
    11	## 1. Responsibilities
    12	
    13	`@relay-assistant/connectivity` provides a typed, in-process signaling layer for internal multi-agent coordination. It is not a generic event bus or pub/sub system. It is the mechanism by which specialists, coordinators, and supporting subsystems communicate state, confidence, handoffs, conflicts, and escalations without verbose transcript exchange.
    14	
    15	**Owns:**
    16	- `ConnectivitySignal` ‚Äî the canonical signal envelope and all supporting types
    17	- Signal emission ‚Äî assigning IDs, timestamps, and initial state
    18	- Signal state machine ‚Äî `emitted ‚Üí active ‚Üí [superseded | expired | resolved]`
    19	- Signal log ‚Äî in-memory, per-thread, queryable log of all signals
    20	- Suppression ‚Äî step-basis or time-basis duplicate detection
    21	- Audience resolution ‚Äî translating semantic audience (`self`, `coordinator`, `selected`, `all`) to recipient identifiers
    22	- Routing escalation hook ‚Äî one-directional interface to routing on escalation emit
    23	- Signal salience ‚Äî defined per signal class; used by suppression and convergence logic
    24	
    25	**Does NOT own:**
    26	- Model invocations or reasoning
    27	- Routing mode selection or model spec (‚Üí `@relay-assistant/routing`)
    28	- Coordinator/specialist orchestration or work assignment (‚Üí `@relay-assistant/coordination`)
    29	- Session or surface management
    30	- Transport or delivery (signals are in-process in v1)
    31	
    32	---
    33	
    34	## 2. Signal Envelope
    35	
    36	### 2.1 `ConnectivitySignal`
    37	
    38	```typescript
    39	export interface ConnectivitySignal {
    40	  /** Unique signal ID within the thread. Assigned by the layer on emit. Format: `sig_<nanoid>`. */
    41	  id: string;
    42	
    43	  /** Thread (coordination context) this signal belongs to. */
    44	  threadId: string;
    45	
    46	  /** Identifier of the component emitting this signal (e.g., 'specialist:reviewer', 'memory'). */
    47	  source: string;
    48	
    49	  /** Semantic delivery intent. Resolved to recipient IDs by the layer or SelectedAudienceResolver. */
    50	  audience: SignalAudience;
    51	
    52	  /** Broad intent category. One of five; see ¬ß4. */
    53	  messageClass: MessageClass;
    54	
    55	  /** Narrow semantic within the message class. One of eleven; see ¬ß5. */
    56	  signalClass: SignalClass;
    57	
    58	  /**
    59	   * Routing urgency.
    60	   * - 'low': informational; does not interrupt current routing mode
    61	   * - 'normal': advisory; may influence next routing decision
    62	   * - 'high': may trigger immediate routing mode change via escalation hook
    63	   * - 'critical': must trigger routing escalation; coordinator must acknowledge; never suppressed
    64	   */
    65	  priority: SignalPriority;
    66	
    67	  /**
    68	   * Salience grade for this signal, 0.0‚Äì1.0.
    69	   * Encodes how decision-relevant this signal is relative to the current thread state.
    70	   * Required for `confidence.*` and `conflict.*` signal classes.
    71	   * Optional for all others.
    72	   * Connectivity stores and forwards the value; it does not evaluate it.
    73	   * Interpretation is the responsibility of coordination and routing.
    74	   *
    75	   * Guidance by signal class:
    76	   * - confidence.high ‚Üí 0.8‚Äì1.0
    77	   * - confidence.medium ‚Üí 0.4‚Äì0.79
    78	   * - confidence.low ‚Üí 0.1‚Äì0.39
    79	   * - confidence.blocker ‚Üí 0.0
    80	   * - conflict.active ‚Üí required; must reflect how blocking the conflict is
    81	   * - conflict.resolved ‚Üí optional; set to the value from the resolved signal
    82	   */
    83	  confidence?: number;
    84	
    85	  /**
    86	   * One-sentence description of the signal. Required.
    87	   * Used for suppression deduplication key and signal log display.
    88	   * Should be specific enough for a coordinator to act on without reading `details`.
    89	   */
    90	  summary: string;
    91	
    92	  /**
    93	   * Optional extended detail. Should be compact ‚Äî not a reasoning transcript.
    94	   * Routing layer may omit this from forwarding in 'cheap' mode.
    95	   * Max recommended length: 500 characters.
    96	   */
    97	  details?: string;
    98	
    99	  /**
   100	   * ID of the signal this supersedes. When set, the targeted signal transitions to 'superseded'.
   101	   * Use when emitting an update that makes a prior signal obsolete.
   102	   */
   103	  replaces?: string;
   104	
   105	  /**
   106	   * Step number at which this signal auto-expires.
   107	   * The layer transitions state to 'expired' when `advanceStep()` increments past this value.
   108	   * When omitted, the signal does not auto-expire.
   109	   */
   110	  expiresAtStep?: number;
   111	
   112	  /** ISO-8601 timestamp. Set by the layer during emit(). */
