   238	
   239	## 6. Signal Salience
   240	
   241	**Salience** is the degree to which a signal is decision-relevant relative to the current thread state. It is expressed through the `confidence` field (0.0‚Äì1.0) when applicable, and through `priority` for all signals.
   242	
   243	Connectivity does not evaluate salience. It stores and forwards it. Coordination and routing interpret it.
   244	
   245	**Salience rules:**
   246	- `priority='critical'` signals are always high-salience; they bypass suppression and must be delivered
   247	- `priority='high'` signals with `confidence < 0.2` on a `confidence.*` class indicate a high-salience blocker
   248	- `priority='low'` signals with no `confidence` field are the lowest-salience; suppressed most aggressively
   249	- For suppression purposes, two signals with identical `threadId + source + signalClass + audience` are treated as the same logical signal regardless of salience value (the existing signal is returned unchanged)
   250	
   251	---
   252	
   253	## 7. Suppression
   254	
   255	Suppression prevents redundant signals from accumulating within a coordination window.
   256	
   257	### 7.1 Duplicate Definition
   258	
   259	Two signals are considered duplicates when all of the following are identical:
   260	- `threadId`

