     1	# v1 Connectivity Scope ‚Äî `@relay-assistant/connectivity`
     2	
     3	**Date:** 2026-04-11
     4	**Status:** SCOPE_LOCKED
     5	**Prerequisite:** v1 foundation integration (core + sessions + surfaces) ‚Äî PASS_WITH_FOLLOWUPS
     6	
     7	---
     8	
     9	## 1. What v1 Connectivity Absolutely Includes
    10	
    11	### 1.1 Signal Envelope and Types
    12	
    13	The package exports `ConnectivitySignal` and all supporting types as the canonical signal contract. Every signal carries:
    14	
    15	- `id` ‚Äî unique within the thread, assigned by the layer on emit
    16	- `threadId` ‚Äî scopes the signal to a coordination context
    17	- `source` ‚Äî identifies the emitting component
    18	- `audience` ‚Äî semantic delivery intent (`self`, `coordinator`, `selected`, `all`)
    19	- `messageClass` ‚Äî broad intent category (one of five; see ¬ß4)
    20	- `signalClass` ‚Äî narrow semantic within the message class (one of eleven; see ¬ß4)
    21	- `priority` ‚Äî routing urgency (`low`, `normal`, `high`, `critical`)
    22	- `confidence` ‚Äî optional numeric stability grade (0.0‚Äì1.0), required for confidence and conflict signals
    23	- `summary` ‚Äî one-sentence description, required, used for suppression deduplication
    24	- `details` ‚Äî optional compact extension, not a transcript
    25	- `replaces` ‚Äî optional signal ID; triggers supersession of the replaced signal
    26	- `expiresAtStep` ‚Äî optional step number for automatic expiry
    27	- `emittedAt` ‚Äî ISO-8601 timestamp, set by the layer
    28	- `state` ‚Äî lifecycle state, managed by the layer
    29	
    30	### 1.2 Signal Lifecycle State Machine
    31	
    32	```
    33	emitted ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚ñ∫ active ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚ñ∫ superseded   (a newer signal with `replaces` targeting this ID)
    34	                   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ‚ñ∫ expired      (expiresAtStep reached via advanceStep)
    35	                   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ‚ñ∫ resolved     (explicitly resolved by emitter or coordinator)
    36	```
    37	
    38	Five states: `emitted`, `active`, `superseded`, `expired`, `resolved`. The signal log retains all signals regardless of terminal state. State transitions are updated in place.
    39	
    40	### 1.3 In-Memory Signal Log
    41	
    42	A `Map<threadId, ConnectivitySignal[]>` storing all signals for all active threads. Supports:
    43	
    44	- `emit(input)` ‚Äî create and store a signal, assign id and timestamp, return stored signal
    45	- `get(signalId)` ‚Äî retrieve a single signal by ID
    46	- `query(query)` ‚Äî retrieve signals with filters by source, messageClass, signalClass, state, priority, time range, with limit and sort order
    47	- `resolve(signalId)` ‚Äî transition a signal to `resolved`, idempotent
    48	- `advanceStep(threadId)` ‚Äî increment step counter, expire signals past their `expiresAtStep`
    49	
    50	### 1.4 Suppression
    51	
    52	Duplicate detection prevents redundant signals within a suppression window. Two signals are duplicates when they share the same `threadId` + `source` + `signalClass` + `audience` and neither has been resolved or superseded.
    53	
    54	Suppression basis is configurable:
    55	
    56	- **step-basis** ‚Äî duplicates suppressed within the same step; `advanceStep()` resets the window
    57	- **time-basis** ‚Äî duplicates suppressed within a configurable `windowMs` (default 5000ms)
    58	
    59	When suppressed, `emit()` returns the existing signal unchanged. Callers detect suppression by comparing the returned signal's `id` to what they expected.
    60	
    61	### 1.5 Callback System
    62	
    63	- `onSignal(callback)` ‚Äî register a callback fired on every `emitted`, `superseded`, `resolved`, and `expired` event
    64	- `offSignal(callback)` ‚Äî remove a previously registered callback
    65	
    66	This is the primary integration point. Coordination and routing layers subscribe to signal events without polling.
    67	
    68	### 1.6 Audience Resolution
    69	
    70	- `self`, `coordinator`, `all` ‚Äî resolved by the layer directly based on the thread's registered components
    71	- `selected` ‚Äî resolved by calling a `SelectedAudienceResolver` function registered by the coordination layer
    72	
    73	The `registerSelectedResolver(resolver)` method accepts a function `(signal: ConnectivitySignal) => string[]` that returns the component IDs to notify. Coordination owns the resolver implementation. Connectivity owns the interface.
    74	
    75	### 1.7 Routing Escalation Hook
    76	
    77	Connectivity can influence routing decisions without owning routing (see ¬ß5 for full treatment). The v1 mechanism:
    78	
    79	- `ConnectivityLayerConfig` accepts an optional `routingEscalationHook: RoutingEscalationHook`
    80	- When an escalation signal (`escalation.interrupt` or `escalation.uncertainty`) is emitted, `emit()` synchronously calls `routingEscalationHook.onEscalation(signal)`
    81	- The hook returns `RequestedRoutingMode` (`'cheap' | 'fast' | 'deep'`) or `void`
    82	- Connectivity does not act on the returned mode. It is the routing layer's responsibility to apply or ignore it.
    83	
    84	### 1.8 Factory Function
    85	
    86	```typescript
    87	createConnectivityLayer(config?: ConnectivityLayerConfig): ConnectivityLayer
    88	```
    89	
    90	Returns a thread-aware layer. Multiple threads share one instance. All state is in-process in v1.
    91	
    92	### 1.9 Four Workflow Shapes
    93	
    94	The following workflows are proved in v1 integration tests:
    95	
    96	| ID | Name | Signal path |
    97	|---|---|---|
    98	| WF-C1 | Narrowcast attention | Specialist ‚Üí emit(attention.raise, selected) ‚Üí audience resolver ‚Üí onSignal ‚Üí coordination reads |
    99	| WF-C2 | Reviewer conflict | Specialist A ‚Üí emit(conflict.active, coordinator) ‚Üí onSignal ‚Üí coordination queries ‚Üí arbitrates ‚Üí resolve() |
   100	| WF-C3 | Specialist handoff | Specialist A ‚Üí emit(handoff.ready, selected) ‚Üí onSignal ‚Üí downstream specialist begins ‚Üí coordination resolves |
   101	| WF-C4 | Blocker uncertainty routing | Specialist ‚Üí emit(escalation.uncertainty, high) ‚Üí routingEscalationHook ‚Üí routing returns mode ‚Üí onSignal ‚Üí coordination adjusts |
   102	
   103	### 1.10 Package Boundary and Dependency Rules
   104	
   105	| Direction | Rule |
   106	|---|---|
   107	| Connectivity ‚Üí core | Allowed. Import types only. |
   108	| Connectivity ‚Üí routing | Import `RequestedRoutingMode` type only. Never call routing methods directly. |
   109	| Connectivity ‚Üí sessions | Forbidden. |
   110	| Connectivity ‚Üí surfaces | Forbidden. |
   111	| Connectivity ‚Üí memory | Forbidden. |
   112	| Connectivity ‚Üí coordination | Forbidden. Coordination depends on connectivity, not vice versa. |
   113	| Coordination ‚Üí connectivity | Allowed. Coordination imports and uses `ConnectivityLayer`. |
   114	| Routing ‚Üí connectivity | Allowed. Routing implements `RoutingEscalationHook`. |
   115	
