   117	
   118	## 2. What Is Explicitly Deferred Beyond v1
   119	
   120	### 2.1 Not in v1
   121	
   122	| Capability | Reason for deferral | Target |
   123	|---|---|---|
   124	| Distributed / cross-process signal delivery | v1 is single-process; distribution requires transport integration | v1.2+ |
   125	| Persistent signal log | In-memory only; persistence requires storage adapter | v1.2+ |
   126	| Signal log retention beyond thread lifetime | Signals scoped to thread; cross-thread history requires persistence | v1.2+ |
   127	| Tenant-aware signal routing | No multi-tenant semantics in v1; cloud concern | Cloud adapter |
   128	| Cloud observability pipelines | OSS logging only; hosted telemetry is adapter-based | Cloud adapter |
   129	| Product-specific signal classes | The 5 message classes and 11 signal classes are the complete v1 vocabulary; products do not add custom classes in v1 | v1.1+ |
   130	| Provider-specific real-time delivery | In-process callbacks only; WebSocket/SSE delivery is product concern | Product layer |
   131	| Async `emit()` | v1 `emit()` is synchronous; async complicates call sites and is unnecessary without distributed delivery | v1.2 (with distribution) |
   132	| Maximum active signals per thread | No cap in v1; runaway signaling protection deferred | v1.1 |
   133	| Broadcast suppression policy | No differentiated suppression for `audience='all'` vs narrowcast | Before WF-C2 hardening |
   134	| Queued vs immediate routing mode application | v1 applies routing hints immediately via hook; queuing deferred | Before WF-C4 hardening |
   135	
   136	### 2.2 Boundaries That Will Not Move
   137	
   138	These are permanent scope exclusions, not deferrals:
   139	
   140	- Connectivity will never own model invocations or reasoning
   141	- Connectivity will never own message routing decisions (routing's job)
   142	- Connectivity will never own coordinator/specialist orchestration (coordination's job)
   143	- Connectivity will never own session or surface management
   144	- Connectivity will never be a generic pub/sub system with topics and subscriptions
   145	- Connectivity will never produce user-visible messages; signals are internal only
   146	
   147	---
   148	
   149	## 3. Connectivity vs Adjacent Packages
   150	
   151	### 3.1 Connectivity vs Coordination
   152	
   153	| Dimension | Connectivity | Coordination |
   154	|---|---|---|
   155	| Core question | "What signal should move between participants right now?" | "Who is doing what work?" |
   156	| Owns | Signal envelope, lifecycle, suppression, audience resolution, escalation hook | Specialist assignment, output collection, synthesis orchestration |
   157	| Call direction | Coordination calls connectivity (`emit`, `query`, `resolve`, `onSignal`). Connectivity never calls coordination. | Coordination provides `SelectedAudienceResolver` to connectivity. |
   158	| Example | Reviewer emits `conflict.active` to coordinator | Coordinator decides whether to re-delegate or arbitrate after receiving the conflict signal |
   159	
   160	The boundary is strict: connectivity is the signaling mechanism; coordination is the decision-maker that uses signals as input. Coordination registers an `onSignal` callback to react. Coordination provides the `SelectedAudienceResolver` so connectivity can resolve `audience='selected'` without knowing the coordination topology.
   161	
   162	### 3.2 Connectivity vs Routing
   163	
   164	| Dimension | Connectivity | Routing |
   165	|---|---|---|
   166	| Core question | "What urgency and confidence does this signal carry?" | "What model tier and cost envelope should this invocation use?" |
   167	| Owns | Signal classes, priority levels, escalation emission | Mode selection (`cheap`/`fast`/`deep`), model spec, cost tracking |
   168	| Call direction | One-directional: connectivity calls routing's `RoutingEscalationHook.onEscalation()` during escalation emit. Routing never calls connectivity. | Routing implements `RoutingEscalationHook` and registers it with connectivity at initialization. |
   169	| Example | Specialist emits `escalation.uncertainty` with `priority='high'` ‚Üí connectivity calls hook | Router receives the signal, returns `'deep'` as requested mode, applies it to subsequent `decide()` calls |
   170	
   171	Connectivity does not know what routing does with the escalation. Routing does not emit signals. The interface between them is a single hook with a single method.
   172	
   173	### 3.3 Connectivity vs Relay Transport
   174	
   175	| Dimension | Connectivity | Relay Transport |
   176	|---|---|---|
   177	| Core question | "Why does this signal exist, who should see it, and when can it be dropped?" | "How do bytes move from A to B?" |
   178	| Owns | Signal semantics, audience intent, suppression, lifecycle | Delivery infrastructure, queues, connections, retries |
   179	| Interaction in v1 | None. Signals are in-process. No transport layer involved. | Transport delivers user-facing messages via surfaces, not internal signals. |
   180	| Future interaction | When signals cross process boundaries (v1.2+), transport becomes the delivery mechanism for signals. Connectivity will define signal serialization; transport will deliver it. | Transport will gain a signal delivery adapter alongside its existing message delivery. |
   181	
   182	In v1, connectivity has zero runtime dependency on transport. Signals are function calls and callbacks within a single Node process.
   183	
   184	---
   185	
   186	## 4. Minimum Signal Classes and Semantics
   187	
   188	### 4.1 Message Classes (5)
   189	
   190	| Class | Semantic | When to use |
   191	|---|---|---|
   192	| `attention` | Something another component should consider; not urgent | Memory finds context that changes likely intent; retrieval finds contradictory background |
   193	| `confidence` | Stability grade of a specialist's current output | Specialist declares how trustworthy its result is before synthesis consumes it |
   194	| `conflict` | Two active views disagree in a way that affects the final answer | Reviewer evidence contradicts the current draft; two specialists propose incompatible actions |
   195	| `handoff` | Downstream component can proceed; this specialist is done with its step | Planner finished a plan; reviewer completed a pass; memory enrichment is ready for synthesis |
   196	| `escalation` | Current path should change immediately; high urgency | Policy issue discovered; unsafe action path; uncertainty too high for current routing mode |
   197	
   198	### 4.2 Signal Classes (11)
   199	
   200	| Signal class | Parent message class | Semantic |
   201	|---|---|---|
   202	| `attention.raise` | attention | Flag something for another's consideration |
   203	| `confidence.high` | confidence | Output is stable and well-supported |
   204	| `confidence.medium` | confidence | Output is reasonable but has caveats |
   205	| `confidence.low` | confidence | Output is speculative; coordinator should weigh carefully |
   206	| `confidence.blocker` | confidence | Cannot produce useful output without more input |
   207	| `conflict.active` | conflict | Conflict currently exists and is unresolved |
   208	| `conflict.resolved` | conflict | Previously flagged conflict has been resolved |
   209	| `handoff.ready` | handoff | Output is ready for downstream consumption |
   210	| `handoff.partial` | handoff | Partial output available; more coming |
   211	| `escalation.interrupt` | escalation | Immediate path change required |
   212	| `escalation.uncertainty` | escalation | High uncertainty; requesting routing mode change |
   213	
   214	### 4.3 What This Vocabulary Excludes (and Why)
   215	
   216	The following signal classes appear in the earlier docs spike but are **not** in the v1 vocabulary:
   217	
   218	| Excluded | Reason |
   219	|---|---|
   220	| `attention.dismiss` | Dismissal is handled by `resolve()`, not by a separate signal class |
   221	| `handoff.blocked` | Blocked state is expressed by `confidence.blocker`; a separate handoff-blocked class creates ambiguity about which to use |
   222	| `escalation.required` / `escalation.immediate` | Consolidated into `escalation.interrupt` (immediate) and `escalation.uncertainty` (requesting deeper routing); two classes cover the same semantic space with clearer distinction |
   223	| `conflict.detected` | Renamed to `conflict.active` for consistency with the lifecycle model (a conflict is a state, not a one-time event) |
   224	
   225	The vocabulary is intentionally small. Products that need finer distinctions use the `details` field on the signal, not new signal classes.
   226	
   227	### 4.4 Priority Semantics
   228	
   229	| Priority | Effect on routing | Effect on suppression |
   230	|---|---|---|
   231	| `low` | Informational; does not influence routing mode | May be suppressed aggressively |
   232	| `normal` | Advisory; may influence next routing decision | Standard suppression window |
   233	| `high` | May trigger immediate routing mode change via escalation hook | Suppression window shortened or bypassed |
   234	| `critical` | Must trigger routing escalation; coordinator must acknowledge | Never suppressed |
   235	
   236	### 4.5 Confidence Field Semantics
   237	
   238	The `confidence` field is a number from 0.0 to 1.0. It is:
   239	
   240	- **Required** on `confidence.*` and `conflict.*` signal classes
   241	- **Optional** on all other signal classes
   242	- **Interpreted** by coordination and routing, not by connectivity itself
   243	
   244	Connectivity stores and forwards the value. It does not make decisions based on the value. This keeps the interpretation logic in coordination and routing where it belongs.
   245	
   246	---
   247	
   248	## 5. How Connectivity Influences Routing Without Owning Routing
   249	
   250	### 5.1 The Problem
   251	
   252	A specialist may discover that the current routing mode (`cheap` or `fast`) cannot produce an answer that meets the fixed quality bar. The system needs a way to request a deeper routing mode without connectivity making routing decisions directly.
   253	
   254	### 5.2 The v1 Mechanism
   255	
   256	The interaction is one-directional and hook-based:
   257	
   258	```
   259	Specialist ‚îÄ‚îÄemit(escalation.uncertainty, priority=high)‚îÄ‚îÄ‚ñ∫ ConnectivityLayer
   260	ConnectivityLayer ‚îÄ‚îÄroutingEscalationHook.onEscalation(signal)‚îÄ‚îÄ‚ñ∫ Router

