    98	### Step 2 ‚Äî Signal Log (In-Memory)
    99	
   100	**File:** `src/id.ts`
   101	
   102	```typescript
   103	import { nanoid } from 'nanoid';
   104	export function generateSignalId(): string {
   105	  return `sig_${nanoid()}`;
   106	}
   107	```
   108	
   109	**File:** `src/log.ts`
   110	
   111	```typescript
   112	class SignalLog {
   113	  private readonly log: Map<string, ConnectivitySignal[]>;
   114	
   115	  emit(input: EmitSignalInput): ConnectivitySignal;  // validates, assigns id/emittedAt/state
   116	  get(signalId: string): ConnectivitySignal | null;
   117	  query(query: SignalQuery): ConnectivitySignal[];
   118	  getByThread(threadId: string): ConnectivitySignal[];
   119	}
   120	```
   121	
   122	**`emit()` implementation details:**
   123	1. Validate input ‚Äî throw `SignalValidationError` on violations:
   124	   - `threadId`, `source`, `summary` non-empty
   125	   - `signalClass` consistent with `messageClass`
   126	   - `confidence` present and in range when required
   127	   - `replaces` references a valid signal in same thread (if set)
   128	2. Assign `id = generateSignalId()`, `emittedAt = new Date().toISOString()`, `state = 'emitted'`
   129	3. Append to `log.get(threadId) ?? []`
   130	4. Return stored signal
   131	
   132	**`query()` implementation details:**
   133	- Default `state` filter: `['emitted', 'active']`
   134	- Apply all filters with AND semantics
   135	- Default `limit`: 50
   136	- Default `order`: `'newest'` (sort by `emittedAt` descending)
   137	- Array-valued filters (`messageClass[]`, etc.) use OR semantics within the filter
   138	
   139	**Tests (`log.test.ts`):**
   140	- emit assigns id (starts with `sig_`) and ISO-8601 `emittedAt`
   141	- emit sets initial `state='emitted'`
   142	- get returns null for unknown ID
   143	- query with `messageClass` filter returns only matching signals
   144	- query with `state=['active']` excludes emitted signals
   145	- query with `limit=2` returns at most 2 results
   146	- query with `order='oldest'` returns chronological order
   147	- query on unknown `threadId` returns empty array
   148	
   149	---
   150	
   151	### Step 3 ‚Äî State Transitions
   152	
   153	**File:** `src/lifecycle.ts`
   154	
   155	```typescript
   156	class SignalLifecycle {
   157	  resolve(log: SignalLog, signalId: string): ConnectivitySignal;
   158	  supersede(log: SignalLog, replacedId: string): ConnectivitySignal;
   159	}
   160	```
   161	
   162	**`resolve()` behavior:**
   163	- Retrieve signal by ID; throw `SignalNotFoundError` if not found
   164	- If already `'resolved'`, return unchanged (idempotent)
   165	- If in terminal state (`'superseded'`, `'expired'`), throw `ConnectivityError` (cannot resolve terminal state)
   166	- Transition `state` to `'resolved'`
   167	
   168	**`supersede()` behavior:**
   169	- Called by `emit()` when `input.replaces` is set
   170	- Retrieve the replaced signal; throw `SignalNotFoundError` if not found
   171	- If already in a terminal state, throw `ConnectivityError`
   172	- Transition `state` to `'superseded'`
   173	
   174	**Tests (`lifecycle.test.ts`):**
   175	- resolve transitions `emitted` ‚Üí `resolved`
   176	- resolve transitions `active` ‚Üí `resolved`
   177	- resolve is idempotent on already-resolved signal
   178	- resolve throws on superseded signal
   179	- resolve throws on unknown signal ID
   180	- supersede via `emit(replaces=...)` transitions the target to `superseded`
   181	- supersede of terminal signal throws
   182	
   183	---
   184	
   185	### Step 4 ‚Äî Suppression
   186	
   187	**File:** `src/suppression.ts`
   188	
   189	```typescript
   190	class SuppressionWindow {
   191	  constructor(config: SuppressionConfig);
   192	
   193	  /**
   194	   * Returns the existing signal if the input is a duplicate within the window.
   195	   * Returns null if the signal is not suppressed (should be created).
   196	   */
   197	  check(
   198	    input: EmitSignalInput,
   199	    existingSignals: ConnectivitySignal[],
   200	  ): ConnectivitySignal | null;
   201	
   202	  /**
   203	   * Called by advanceStep(). Resets the step window.
   204	   */
   205	  advanceStep(): void;
   206	}
   207	```
   208	
   209	**Duplicate key:** `threadId + source + signalClass + audience`
   210	
   211	**Suppression exclusions:**
   212	- `priority='critical'` ‚Äî never suppressed
   213	- Signal is already resolved or superseded ‚Äî not considered a duplicate
   214	
   215	**Step-basis:** Window resets on each `advanceStep()` call. All non-terminal signals from the same step count as potential duplicates.
   216	
   217	**Time-basis:** Signal is a duplicate if an existing non-terminal signal with the same key was emitted within the last `windowMs` milliseconds.
   218	
   219	**Tests (`suppression.test.ts`):**
   220	- Second `emit()` with identical key returns first signal unchanged
   221	- Suppressed emit does not add a new entry to the log
   222	- Different `signalClass` is not suppressed
   223	- Different `audience` is not suppressed
   224	- `priority='critical'` bypasses suppression
   225	- Resolved signal does not count as duplicate; new signal is created
   226	- Step advance resets the step window
   227	- Time window: signal outside window is not suppressed
   228	
   229	---
   230	
   231	### Step 5 ‚Äî `advanceStep()` and Expiry
   232	
   233	**File:** `src/log.ts` (extend)
   234	
   235	```typescript
   236	advanceStep(threadId: string): ConnectivitySignal[];  // returns expired signals
   237	```
   238	
   239	**Implementation:**
   240	1. Increment internal step counter for `threadId` (initialize at 0 if not set)
   241	2. Scan `log.get(threadId)` for signals where `expiresAtStep !== undefined && expiresAtStep <= currentStep`
   242	3. Filter to non-terminal states only
   243	4. Transition each to `state='expired'`
   244	5. Reset the suppression window for step-basis config
   245	6. Return the list of expired signals (for callback firing)
   246	
   247	**Tests (`step.test.ts`):**
   248	- Signal without `expiresAtStep` does not expire
   249	- Signal with `expiresAtStep=1` expires after one `advanceStep()` call
   250	- Signal with `expiresAtStep=2` does not expire after one `advanceStep()`
   251	- Already-terminal signals are not processed by expiry scan
   252	- `advanceStep()` on unknown thread is a no-op
   253	
   254	---
   255	
   256	### Step 6 ‚Äî `onSignal` / `offSignal`
   257	
   258	**File:** `src/layer.ts` (callback registry)
   259	
   260	```typescript
   261	class CallbackRegistry {
   262	  register(callback: SignalCallback): void;
   263	  unregister(callback: SignalCallback): void;
   264	  fire(signal: ConnectivitySignal, event: SignalEvent): void;
   265	}
   266	```
   267	
   268	**Firing rules:**
   269	- Fire after every state transition: `emit()` ‚Üí `'emitted'`, `supersede` ‚Üí `'superseded'`, `resolve()` ‚Üí `'resolved'`, `advanceStep()` expiry ‚Üí `'expired'`
   270	- Callbacks are called synchronously in registration order
   271	- Exceptions in callbacks are caught and logged; they do not abort subsequent callbacks
   272	- When `advanceStep()` expires multiple signals, `'expired'` fires once per expired signal
   273	
   274	**Tests (`callbacks.test.ts`):**
   275	- `onSignal` callback fires with `event='emitted'` on emit
   276	- `onSignal` callback fires with `event='resolved'` on resolve
   277	- `onSignal` callback fires with `event='superseded'` when signal is replaced
   278	- `onSignal` callback fires with `event='expired'` for each expired signal on `advanceStep()`
   279	- `offSignal` removes the callback; it does not fire after removal
   280	- Multiple callbacks all fire; callback exception does not block subsequent callbacks
   281	- Callback fires even for suppressed emit? **No** ‚Äî suppressed emit returns the existing signal without firing a new event
   282	
   283	---
   284	
   285	### Step 7 ‚Äî Audience Resolution
   286	
   287	**File:** `src/audience.ts`
   288	
   289	```typescript
   290	class AudienceResolver {
   291	  registerSelectedResolver(resolver: SelectedAudienceResolver): void;
   292	  resolve(signal: ConnectivitySignal): string[];
   293	}
   294	```
   295	
   296	**Resolution rules:**
   297	- `'self'` ‚Üí `[signal.source]`
   298	- `'coordinator'` ‚Üí `['coordinator']` (the layer uses the literal string `'coordinator'` as the coordinator component ID in v1; this is sufficient for in-process routing)
   299	- `'selected'` ‚Üí calls `SelectedAudienceResolver(signal)`, or `[]` if no resolver is registered
   300	- `'all'` ‚Üí returns all component IDs registered with the thread (in v1, this is the set of all sources that have emitted signals on the thread, plus `'coordinator'`)
   301	
   302	The resolved recipient IDs are not stored on `ConnectivitySignal` in v1. They are computed at emit time and used only for callback targeting. `onSignal` callbacks always fire to all registered listeners regardless of audience (coordination decides what to do with signals not addressed to it).
   303	
   304	**Tests (`audience.test.ts`):**
   305	- `audience='self'` resolves to `[signal.source]`
   306	- `audience='coordinator'` resolves to `['coordinator']`
   307	- `audience='selected'` calls registered resolver with the signal
   308	- `audience='selected'` with no resolver returns `[]`
   309	- `audience='all'` returns all thread participants
   310	- Registering a new resolver replaces the prior one
   311	
   312	---
   313	
   314	### Step 8 ‚Äî Routing Escalation Hook
   315	
   316	**File:** `src/layer.ts` (wired in `createConnectivityLayer`)
   317	
   318	**Implementation in `emit()`:**
   319	
   320	```
   321	if (signalClass === 'escalation.interrupt' || signalClass === 'escalation.uncertainty') {
   322	  if (config.routingEscalationHook) {
   323	    const requestedMode = config.routingEscalationHook.onEscalation(signal);
   324	    // requestedMode is returned to routing; connectivity does not store or act on it
   325	  }
   326	}
   327	```
   328	
   329	The hook is called **after** the signal is stored and **before** `onSignal` callbacks fire. This ensures the signal exists in the log when the hook executes (routing may call `query()` inside `onEscalation` if needed, though this is not required).
   330	
   331	**Tests (`routing.test.ts`):**
   332	- Mock hook is called with the full `ConnectivitySignal` when `escalation.interrupt` is emitted
   333	- Mock hook is called when `escalation.uncertainty` is emitted
   334	- Mock hook is NOT called for non-escalation signals
   335	- Hook returning `'deep'` does not change any connectivity state
   336	- Hook returning `void` does not throw
   337	- `onSignal` callback still fires when hook is registered
   338	- `onSignal` callback still fires when no hook is registered
   339	- Hook throwing does not prevent `onSignal` callbacks from firing (wrap in try/catch)
